# NextNest — Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
NextNest is a consumer relocation planning platform. Users complete a conversational intake, receive a personalized move plan, and track progress via a dashboard. MVP focus: intake -> plan generation -> dashboard -> magic link auth.

## Tech Stack
- **Framework:** Next.js 14+ (App Router)
- **Language:** TypeScript (strict mode)
- **Styling:** TailwindCSS v4 + shadcn/ui
- **Database:** PostgreSQL on Railway
- **ORM:** Drizzle ORM
- **Auth:** Auth.js v5 (magic link via Resend, no passwords)
- **Email:** Resend (magic links + move reminders)
- **Validation:** Zod (runtime input/payload validation)
- **Deployment:** Railway (web app + database)
- **iOS:** Capacitor 5+ (live URL mode)

## Architecture Rules
- Use the App Router (`/app` directory). No Pages Router.
- All components are functional with hooks. No class components.
- Server Components by default. Add `"use client"` only when needed.
- Co-locate route-specific components: `/app/(routes)/feature/_components/`
- Shared UI in `/components/ui/`. Shared logic in `/lib/`. Types in `/types/`.
- One component per file. File name matches export name (PascalCase).

## File Structure
```
/src
  /app                — App Router pages and API routes
  /components/ui      — shadcn/ui components
  /components/landing — Landing page sections
  /components/intake  — Intake step components
  /components/dashboard — Dashboard widgets
  /components/admin   — Admin components
  /components/layout  — Navbar, Footer, Sidebar
  /lib/db             — Drizzle client + schema + migrations
  /lib                — Utilities, auth config, email, plan engine
  /hooks              — Custom React hooks
  /types              — TypeScript interfaces
  /constants          — App-wide constants
```

## Sprint Protocol
1. **Plan** — Discuss in Ask Mode. Define types/interfaces FIRST.
2. **Scaffold** — Create file structure and types.
3. **Implement** — Build logic. One feature per session.
4. **Validate** — Run lint, type-check, build. Fix all errors.
5. **Review** — Check edge cases, error handling, accessibility.

## Validation Commands
After every meaningful change, run:
```
npm run lint
npx tsc --noEmit
npm run build
```

## Code Standards
- async/await only. No `.then()` chains.
- All functions have JSDoc docstrings.
- No `any` type. Use `unknown` + type guards when uncertain.
- Error boundaries around every route segment.
- API routes return typed responses: `{ data, error, status }`.
- Zod validation on all user inputs and API payloads.
- Loading and error states for every async operation.

## Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase (`MoveCountdown.tsx`)
- Hooks: camelCase with `use` prefix (`useMoveTimeline.ts`)
- Utils/lib: camelCase (`calculateReadinessScore.ts`)
- Types: PascalCase (`IntakeFormData`, `TimelineMilestone`)
- API routes: kebab-case folders (`/api/generate-plan/route.ts`)
- Database columns: snake_case

## UI/UX Standards
- Design: calm, clean, encouraging. Airbnb-inspired.
- TailwindCSS only. No inline styles.
- Consistent spacing: `p-4`, `gap-4`, `space-y-4` baseline.
- Mobile-first responsive. Test at 375px, 768px, 1280px.
- Interactive elements must have hover/focus/active states.
- Skeleton loaders for async content. No layout shift.
- Warm neutrals + teal accent. No harsh or corporate tones.

## Database Conventions
- All tables: `id` (UUID), `created_at`, `updated_at`.
- Drizzle ORM for all queries. No raw SQL unless justified.
- Client: `/lib/db/index.ts`. Schema: `/lib/db/schema.ts`.
- Never expose database credentials to the client.

## Git Discipline
- Branch naming: `feature/intake-flow`, `fix/dashboard-countdown`.
- Conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, `chore:`.
- New Composer session per feature. Don't carry stale context.
- Update these rules when new conventions emerge.

## What NOT to Do
- Don't install packages without justification.
- Don't abstract "for the future." Build for the current sprint.
- Don't write comments that narrate code. Comments explain WHY.
- Don't skip error handling.
- Don't store sensitive data in localStorage.
